  "market_context": "Intraday price action on apoZ following a sweep of previous day highs, occurring during the New York session (08:30–11:00 EST) on April 25, 2025. The market formed a bearish reversal after liquidity sweep and progressed into a continuation lower.",
  "key_observation": "The analyst emphasized that while multiple PD arrays (turtle soup, inversion, breaker block, FVG) were present, he chose to focus solely on 'change in state of delivery' for repeatable entries, ignoring other confluences to simplify his model.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the initial sweep of previous day highs (turtle soup) as the first low-confirmation reversal signal.",
    "Step 2: Observe the closure below the fair value gap (inversion) as higher-confirmation signal that the high is likely intact.",
    "Step 3: Wait for and confirm the change in state of delivery — price closing below the series of up-close candles that formed the swing high.",
    "Step 4: Use the confirmed change in state of delivery as the sole entry trigger, placing stop above the swing high or body level of the opposing candles.",
    "Step 5: Drop to 3-minute timeframe to verify the same sequence (sweep → inversion → CISD) and confirm the breaker block and FVG are respected but not used for entry.",
    "Step 6: Anticipate continuation lower by watching for retests of opposing candles (up-close into resistance) and expecting them to hold as sell zones."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade executed short at ~34.000 with stop near 34.010; price continued lower to ~33.470, achieving >2R reward.",
  "lessons": "Consistency comes from focusing on one high-probability PD array (e.g., change in state of delivery) rather than cluttering the chart with multiple confluences. Mastery of a single repeatable setup yields better journal data and edge than chasing all signals.",
